{"key":"processedPost-6135528","value":{"id":6135528,"first":6135303,"last":6135528,"when":1160054773,"utime":"10/05/06 04:26 PM","content":"Right.&nbsp; Ambient indoor light will help to speed up colonizing mycelium in jars or filter patch bags.&nbsp; I have proved this for years by using a shelf in my bedroom for incubation of dozens of species.&nbsp; None are affected in a negative way by light during colonization.&nbsp; The old myth of 'incubate in total darkness' is bunk.&nbsp; Stamets himself has changed his advice and newer revisions of his books do not have any suggestion to incubate in darkness.<br /><br />Your incubator is set too high.&nbsp; Personally, I'd use room temperature for simplicity and a reduction in contaminants.&nbsp; Nearly all contaminants of mushroom culture are stimulated by higher temperatures.&nbsp; If your house is over 72F, your jars will colonize within a few days of the same speed they will at 84F, and you'll have fewer contamination problems with bacteria and especially Mucor, the black pin mold which is stimulated by temperatures over 85F within the jars.<br />RR","title":"Re: light on the mycelia"}}